  "prompt": "What is a zero sum game?",
  "response": "A zero-sum game is a concept in game theory and economics where the total gains and losses among the participants balance out to zero. In other words, one player's gain is exactly equal to the losses of another player or players. This means that the sum of the outcomes (wins or losses) in the game is constant, typically zero.\n\nIn a zero-sum game, if one player wins a certain amount of utility, points, or resources, another player loses the same amount. This type of game is often used to illustrate competitive scenarios, where the interests of the participants are directly opposed.\n\nFor example, in a two-player poker game, if Player A wins $100 from Player B, then Player B has lost $100. The net gain and loss sum to zero.\n\nZero-sum games are commonly analyzed in competitive sports, financial trading, and various strategic interactions where resources are scarce and finite. Not all situations are zero-sum; many real-world interactions allow for cooperation or mutual benefit, leading to positive-sum or negative-sum outcomes.",
